Abstract = {In order to reach its audiences, journalism regularly turns to social
   media to promote its articles. This study sets out to ascertain
   competing communicative logics of Facebook posts as opposed to article
   teasers on news outlets' websites. We look at Scandinavian news outlets
   as a most-similar three-country case with at least a third of all news
   consumers regularly using Facebook for news. The study builds on an
   extensive data collection of all Scandinavian news outlets' Facebook
   posts including their respective websites' article teasers over the
   course of 11 months. We investigate the use of news text grammar (e.g.,
   punctuation or the use of pronouns) and social media features (e.g.,
   hashtags or the use of emojis) alongside structural influences from
   individual countries, outlet reach, and ownership. Findings show
   Facebook posts to include less punctuation while employing more calls to
   action through the use of question and exclamation marks. We conclude
   with a reinvigorated call for hierarchical considerations when
   investigating news outlets' social media endeavours through editors'
   experiences, available resources to a news outlet, and institutional
   willingness to align with audiences.},
