Abstract = {Comments that accompany news teasers on social media are often uncivil,
   leading to undesired outcomes for news outlets. Why are readers
   susceptible to the effects of online comments? Are comments perceived as
   memorable or authentic more likely to influence readers? If so, do such
   outcomes occur across multiple types of news? An online experiment was
   conducted to test a 3 (comment valence: positive vs. negative vs. no
   comment control) x 4 (topic type: policy vs. international vs. health
   vs. sports) between-subjects design using a convenience sample recruited
   from Amazon Mechanical Turk (N = 230). Results revealed that negative
   comments decreased news credibility and issue importance through the
   mediating pathway of decreased bandwagon support. The pattern of results
   was particularly strong among comments perceived as vivid and authentic,
   regardless of the type of news in question. Theoretical and practical
   implications of study findings are discussed.},
