Pages = {340-364},
Month = {MAR 18},
Abstract = {Recent studies found linguistic positivity bias in academic writing,
   that is, researchers tend to present their works with more positive
   words than negative ones. The present study aims to examine the issue
   from a diachronic perspective, and it is probably the first one that
   employed a mixed method of both a small lexicon analysis and sentiment
   analysis in this line of research. Specifically, a series of experiments
   were performed based on a corpus of 775,460 abstracts published between
   1969 and 2019 in 123 scientific journals covering 12 research
   disciplines in life sciences. The results demonstrated a linguistic
   positivity bias in academic writing. More importantly, a significant
   upward trend of linguistic positivity bias was observed over the past 5
   decades. Major communicative functions of positive and negative
   sentences are also analysed. Reasons for this linguistic positivity bias
   are explored from the perspectives of publication pressure/bias,
   employment of linguistic devices to promote research, and language use
   for political correctness purposes. Lastly, implications for authors and
   learners of academic writing and for researchers of sentiment analysis
