   FLH programs represent hybrid spaces where talk emerges naturally for
   social reasons but is framed under an institutional purpose for language
   learning. Given its multi-functional ability to simultaneously
   coordinate both sociable humor and learning-in-interaction, LP emerges
   as a salient resource in such dual-purpose environments. Using a
   multimodal Conversation Analysis of two extended sequences of LP during
   mealtime conversations, this study analyzes how FLH participants deploy
   verbal and embodied resources to organize participation in LP. It then
