   process characterized by the tendency to construct members of an
   opposing party in negative ways. In this article, we examine the
   creation and disruption of othering through the lens of language
   convergence/meaning divergence (LC/MD) and pragmatic ambiguity. LC/MD
   and pragmatic ambiguity framed our case study of the successful
