   Disagreement},
Journal = {DIGITAL JOURNALISM},
Year = {2022},
Volume = {10},
Number = {3},
Pages = {433-451},
Month = {APR 12},
Abstract = {Due to their potential influence on the individual and societal
   formation of opinions, the quality of online discussions has been a
   subject of widespread interest. From a deliberative perspective,
   rational argumentation and critical reflection are central criteria for
   good discourse. Drawing on research on the perception of arguments and
   the conditions of disagreement, we ask how argument strength is linked
   to the likelihood of receiving (reasoned) disagreement and whether the
   discussion norms and technical features set by the news organizations
   moderate this effect. Based on a manual content analysis of 14.690 user
   comments on nine German news websites, we find that comments with a
   higher argument strength are more likely to receive disagreement in
   general and reasoned disagreement in particular. Further, the levels of
   (reasoned) disagreement are higher on platforms with strong discussion
   norms and supporting technical features. The results show that the
   quality of a discussion can be related to both users' argumentation and
   the decisions of the news organizations.},
