Abstract = {How human beings think about, talk about, and organize around sexuality
   is changing. Growing social legitimization for sexual minority
   relationships and a more fluid social understanding of sexual identities
   has shifted how we bound normal sexuality. In the workplace, these
   shifting norms affect employees of all sexual identities who must make
   sense of new policies and complex daily practices. This paper introduces
   the concept of co-sexuality, the push-and-pull process of
   communicatively organizing around sexuality. Using this concept, we take
