Abstract = {In recent years, a number of scholars have taken parties and
   partisanship as objects of normative theorizing. They posit partisanship
   as a fundamentally democratic practice and develop a model of what
   partisans can do at their best to contribute to liberal democracy.
   However, the standards the literature puts forth remain insufficiently
   specified to serve as empirical benchmarks. This article further
   conceptualizes this model of democratic partisanship and offers a
   theoretical framework within which to empirically evaluate the
   democratic merits of partisan discourses. It establishes a series of
   indicators for assessing the extent to which partisan discourse displays
