Abstract = {This study investigates how the use of discourse markers reflects
   speaking fluency in Chinese learners. In this study, 220 min of online
   Chinese courses were transcribed, with 17 Chinese learners and 5 native
   Chinese teachers as participants. Half of the transcribed data were
   drawn from students living in Taipei, Taiwan, a Chinese-speaking
   environment, learning Chinese as a second language. The other portion of
   the data was collected from students living in non-Chinese-speaking
   countries, learning Chinese as a foreign language with little exposure
   to the language outside the classroom. Analysis of the transcripts
   supported the hypothesis that the frequency of discourse markers used by
   individual speakers reflects their fluency in the target language.
