Abstract = {When, in homestays abroad, mealtime is understood as key to the
   maintenance and development of family identity and involves routine
   gathering for nourishment and convivial talk, students attribute much of
   their language learning to these events. In this project, we adopt a
   microgenetic approach to the study of mealtime discourse as a learning
   opportunity for three American high school students of varying
   proficiency in Chinese and their Chinese hosts. Specifically, analysis
   of contextualized language practices at mealtime reveals the qualities
   of these interactions for learning Chinese and American culinary
   practices, related language, and associated ideologies. Our findings
   suggest that even short-term homestays can be particularly rich
   environments for language learning as hosts and students explore
   divergent views on the aesthetic, moral, and health-related dimensions
