Abstract = {This special issue features applied linguistics scholarship that
   cultivates relationships for justice. The collection of papers in this
   special issue challenges the field of applied linguistics to move beyond
   an acknowledgement of social inequities (through observation, analysis,
   and critique) toward cultivating relationships for justice (CRJ) - in
   order to undo past harms and collectively imagine more just futures. The
   authors/collaborators demonstrate how building systemic social change
   involves decentering the individual researcher's interests and instead
   foregrounding processes of collective solidarity (Martinez et al. 2021),
   demonstrating how justice is relational and aspirational. In this
