Abstract = {Both champions and critics of ``neorealism{''} in contemporary
   international relations misinterpret David Hume as an early spokesman
   for a universal and scientific balance-of-power theory. This article
   instead treats Hume's ``Of the Balance of Power,{''} alongside the other
   essays in his Political Discourses (1752), as conceptual resources for a
   historically inflected analysis of state balancing. Hume's defense of
   the balance of power cannot be divorced from his critique of commercial
   warfare in ``Of the Balance of Trade{''} and ``Of the Jealousy of
   Trade.{''} To better appreciate Hume's historical and economic approach
   to foreign policy, this article places Hume in conversation with
   Machiavelli, Guicciardini, Andrew Fletcher, and Montesquieu.
   International relations scholars suspicious of static paradigms should
   reconsider Hume's genealogy of the balance of power, which differs from
   the standard liberal and neorealist accounts. Well before International
   Political Economy developed as a formal subdiscipline, Hume was
