Month = {JAN-MAR},
Abstract = {In this article, we examine gaze direction in responses to polar
   questions using both quantitative and conversation analytic (CA)
   methods. The data come from a novel corpus of conversations in which
   participants wore eye-tracking glasses to obtain direct measures of
   their eye movements. The results show that while most preferred
   responses are produced with gaze toward the questioner, most
   dispreferred responses are produced with gaze aversion. We further
   demonstrate that gaze aversion by respondents can occasion self-repair
   by questioners in the transition space between turns, indicating that
   the relationship between gaze direction and preference is more than a
   mere statistical association. We conclude that gaze direction in
   responses to polar questions functions as a signal of response
   preference. Data are in American, British, and Canadian English.},
