Abstract = {Crowdsourcing platforms are commonly used for research in the
   humanities, social sciences and informatics, including the use of
   crowdworkers to annotate textual material or visuals. Utilizing two
   empirical studies, this article systematically assesses the potential of
   crowdcoding for lessmanifest contents of news texts, here focusing on
   political actor evaluations. Specifically, Study 1 compares the
   reliability and validity of crowdcoded data to that of manual content
   analyses; Study 2 proceeds to investigate the effects of material
   presentation, different types of coding instructions and answer option
   formats on data quality. We find that the performance of the crowd
   recommends crowdcoded data as a reliable and valid alternative to
   manually coded data, also for less manifest contents. While scale
